  "prompt": "What is the amount of Maximum cash deposit in a saving bank account in a single financial year in India?",
  "response": "In India, there is no specific maximum limit for cash deposits in a savings bank account in a single financial year. However, there are certain regulations and guidelines set by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) and the Income Tax Department that you need to be aware of:\n\n1. **Cash Deposit Limit for KYC Compliance**: Banks are required to monitor cash deposits, and frequent or large cash deposits may trigger inquiries to ensure compliance with KYC (Know Your Customer) norms.\n\n2. **Income Tax Regulations**: If you deposit cash of \u20b910 lakh or more in a financial year across all your savings accounts, the bank will report this to the Income Tax Department under the **Annual Information Return (AIR)**. Similarly, if you deposit \u20b950,000 or more in a single transaction, the bank may ask for your PAN (Permanent Account Number).\n\n3. **Tax Implications**: Large cash deposits may attract scrutiny from the Income Tax Department. If the source of the cash cannot be explained, it may be treated as undisclosed income, and you could be liable to pay taxes and penalties.\n\n4. **Demonetization and Anti-Money Laundering Rules**: Post-demonetization, the government has been stringent about cash transactions to curb black money and money laundering. Frequent or large cash deposits may lead to additional documentation requirements.\n\nWhile there is no explicit cap on cash deposits, it is advisable to keep records of all transactions and ensure that the source of funds is legitimate to avoid any legal or tax-related issues. If you are dealing with significant amounts of cash, consulting a financial advisor or tax professional is recommended.",
